latestIgtvVideos.title: San Choy Bao - Tonights dinner in under 20 minutes w. @Rachael_Finch
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
You can try a vegetarian version using a firm tofu, paneer or mushrooms. 

2 spring onions, finely julienne, placed in iced cold water
¼ cup oil
1 small onion, finely diced
2 cloves garlic, finely chopped
1 tsp grated ginger
1 birds eye chilli, seeds removed finely chopped (optional)
500 g chicken mince
150 g green beans, cut into ½ cm dice
1 small carrot, cut into ½ cm dice
3 tbsp hoisin sauce, plus extra to serve
2 tbsp soy sauce
1 tsp honey
1 tsp sesame oil
1 head iceberg lettuce, separated into cups
 
Heat a wok or heavy based fry pan over high heat and add the oil, onion, garlic and ginger and toss until softened (approx 1 minute). Add the chicken mince and fry until lightly browned (approx 3 minutes). Add the beans and carrot and toss for a minute, then add the hoisin, soy sauce, honey, sesame oil and a dash of water as needed. Bring to a simmer and simmer for about 3 minutes until the chicken is cooked through and the vegetables are softened.
 
Serve the chicken mixture with the spring onion, a dash extra hoisin with lettuce cups.

latestIgtvVideos.title: Turkish inspired eggs
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Simmered in @Sacla_au whole cherry tomato and basil pasta sauce.  Filled with eggplant, made slightly spicy, topped with feta cheese, fresh herbs and a squeeze of lemon.  Mouthwatering breakfast, lunch or even dinner, bonus, ready in under 20 minutes! #partner

SERVES 2
PREP TIME 10 minutes
COOK TIME 20 minutes

INGREDIEDIENTS
3 small eggplants
olive oil to brush
1/2 white onion, finely chopped
1 red chilli, finely chopped
3 garlic cloves, crushed
1 tablespoon paprika
3/4 teaspoon cumin
1 jar Sacla tomato and basil
4 eggs
basil, extra, roughly chopped
feta, to serve
salt and pepper

Preheat the oven to 180°C. Line a large baking tray with baking paper.  Slice the eggplant into 1cm thick rounds and brush each side with olive oil using a pastry brush.  Place in a single layer on the baking tray and bake for 25 minutes, turning over after 15 minutes so both sides cook evenly.  Once the eggplant is cooked, remove it from the oven. Chop into smaller pieces.

Place a large frypan on medium heat and add a tablespoon of olive oil.  Add onion and sauté for 3-4 minutes.  Add chilli and garlic and sauté for a further 3 minutes.  Add paprika, cumin, Sacla tomato and basil sauce and cook for 5 minutes.  Add the eggplant and stir to combine and bring to a simmer.  Season with salt and pepper, swirl and create four small divorts and crack the eggs into these.  Cover with a lid and cook to your liking (5-7 minutes). Check frequently as the eggs cook quickly.  Season with salt and pepper and sprinkle feta and fresh basil on top.

Serve with crusty ciabatta bread.

Street Foods of India: Chole Bhature from Delhi – Episode 12 ✨
ㅤ
The moment I land in Delhi, this is always my first stop.
Chole Bhature is Delhi on a plate. Fluffy, fried, spicy, bold… and completely addictive. Hands down one of my all-time favourite street food dishes in India.
Fluffy, golden bhaturas straight out of hot oil, paired with spicy, rich chickpeas simmered with amla, tea leaves, and a riot of spices.
Loud, messy, and absolutely worth every single bite.
Fun fact: Chole Bhature didn’t come from royal kitchens or fancy restaurants — it was born on the streets, perfected by generations of Delhi vendors who turned simple ingredients into an icon.
Want the recipe? Type ‘CHOLE BHATURE’ in the comments, and I’ll send it straight to your inbox!

Today was one of those days in the MasterChef kitchen that hits you right in the heart. I made a dish I was honestly so proud of—oyster ice cream on beef tartare for a surf and turf challenge. Wild, I know. Josh Niland @mrniland looked at me and said, “This is either a top dish or I’ll be walking you out the door.” Thankfully… it was top. 

But the real moment today wasn’t that. It was watching someone I love walk out those same doors.

@rhiplenish Rhiannon, making a friend like you is what this experience is really about. We’ve shared so many moments already—those long chats in the green room, quiet hugs when we needed them most, laughter that made everything feel lighter. You’ve got this energy that just wraps around people. So grounded, so present, so completely yourself. And that’s rare.

This kitchen might test our cooking—but it reveals your heart. And you, my friend, have one of the best.

I’m walking away from today with a dish I’m proud of—but more than that, I’m walking away with a lifelong friend. Love you, Rhi.

You know those places that stop you in your tracks? The Shore Temple in Mahabalipuram did exactly that. I’ve seen a lot of incredible sites while travelling, but this one hit different.

Built in the 8th century by the Pallavas, it’s one of the oldest structural stone temples in South India—and the only one from a complex of seven that still stands today. Centuries of salt, wind, and time, and it’s still here, watching over the Bay of Bengal.

I stood there with the sea behind me and thought about the hands that carved every stone, the devotion behind every detail. It’s humbling. It’s inspiring. And it reminded me why I love to travel—not just for food, but to feel something that stays with you long after you leave.

#ShoreTemple #Mahabalipuram #IncredibleIndia #India

Moonrakers in Mahabalipuram is one of those legendary coastal gems you hear about long before you arrive—and for good reason. Set near the shore temples of this ancient town, it’s known for serving some of the freshest seafood in Tamil Nadu.

I ordered the Chettinad-style chicken, rich with black pepper, fennel, and curry leaves—a fiery, aromatic classic that truly showcases the bold flavours of the region. And the tawa fry? A sizzling whole catch of the day, cooked on a flat iron griddle until crisp on the outside and juicy inside, perfectly spiced with their signature masala.

This spot brings together the soul of Tamil coastal cuisine with a laid-back, no-fuss vibe. If you’re ever in Mahabs, don’t miss it. Order the fish, eat with your hands, and thank me later.

#Mahabalipuram #Moonrakers #Chettinad #TamilNadu  #IncredibleIndia

Mahabalipuram, tucked along the Coromandel Coast in Tamil Nadu, this ancient port city is known for its UNESCO-listed rock-cut temples… but today? I came for the seafood.

At Santana Restaurant, I had the freshest catch of the day—Tawa Fry, a coastal favourite where fish is marinated in a bold, fiery masala and pan-fried on a hot iron griddle. The masala here? A serious flavour bomb. It’s a dry rub of red chilli, turmeric, black pepper, garlic, ginger, curry leaves, and often a touch of tamarind or vinegar for tang.

This technique, popular across coastal South India, especially Tamil Nadu and Kerala, is all about retaining the crispiness on the outside while keeping the fish juicy and tender inside.

Locals tell me the fishermen head out early morning, bring in their catch, and it’s cooked within hours—no fridges, no fuss, just pure freshness. I’m obsessed.

And while I’ve almost cracked their secret masala… if you have your version of the perfect tawa masala—DM me or comment below. Let’s swap notes!

#Mahabalipuram #TamilNaduEats #TawaFry #IndianSeafood #RegionalIndianCuisine #IncredibleIndia

What a week it’s been. I came back from being unwell and landed straight into a pressure test — making that caviar tin dessert from the queen herself, Kirsten Tibballs. Somehow, I held it together.

Then it was go-time with Shannon Bennett for a 20-minute challenge — and I pulled together something I truly loved: seared scallops with coconut beurre blanc, on top of a cabbage base inspired by Manipur’s Singju salad. Smoky, nutty, buttery — it was delicious.

And then Laura brought it home with a prawn cocktail featuring our very own @HotToddyChilli in her secret sauce.

All in a week’s work. Buckle up for Sunday’s elimination — it’s going to be a big one.

Street Foods of India: Ketli Pitha from Assam – Episode 11 ✨

Ever made a cake on top of a kettle? Meet Ketli Pitha—a traditional Assamese sweet stuffed with coconut and jaggery, steamed in the most creative way imaginable!

Born out of pure ingenuity (and a serious love for sweets), Ketli Pitha proves you don’t need fancy equipment to create magic—just rice flour, a kettle, a cloth, and a whole lot of heart.

It’s soft, nutty, warm, and completely addictive—and honestly, one of my new favourite discoveries.

Want the recipe? Type ‘KETLI PITHA’ in the comments and I’ll send it straight to your inbox!
